* It was a common article of the popular belief that a portion of the fallen angels wander in the air and earth and water, and that they appeared to mankind in the shape of fairies, hobgoblins, &c. Giraldus Cambrensis, ltin. Camb. lib. i. c. 12, gives a curious story illustrative of this notion. It was as old as the Anglo-Saxon age, and occurs in the dialogue between Saturn and Solomon (Thorpe’s Analecta, p. 98.) “ Saga me hwider ge-witon ba engelas be Gode wisssocon on heofona rice? , Ic be secge, hyg to-daeldon on bri daelas: anne dael he asette on baeslyftes ge-drif, oherne dael on baes wateres ge-drif, briddan dael on helle neowelnysse.'' In the legend of St. Brandan these fallen spirits appear in the shape of birds.
